  %div{"data-role" => "header"}
    %h1 .addClass()
  #addClass1{"data-role" => "content", "data-theme" => "c"}
    %h2.jq-clearfix.roundTop.section-title
      %span.name .addClass( className )
      %span.returns
        Returns:
        %a.return{:href => "http://docs.jquery.com/Types#jQuery"} jQuery
    .entry-details
      %p.desc
        %strong> Description:
        Adds the specified class(es) to each of the set of matched elements.
      %ul.signatures
        %li#addClass-className.signature
          %h4.name
            %span.versionAdded>
              version added:
              %a{:href => "/category/version/1.0/"} 1.0
            \.addClass( className )
          %p.arguement
            %strong> className
            One or more class names to be added to the class attribute of each matched element.
        %li.signature{:id => "addClass-functionindex, class"}
          %h4.name
            %span.versionAdded>
              version added:
              %a{:href => "/category/version/1.4/"} 1.4
            \.addClass( function(index, class) )
          %p.arguement
            %strong> function(index, class)
            A function returning one or more space-separated class names to be added. Receives the index position of the element in the set and the old class value as arguments.
      .longdesc
        %p It's important to note that this method does not replace a class. It simply adds the class, appending it to any which may already be assigned to the elements.
        %p More than one class may be added at a time, separated by a space, to the set of matched elements, like so:
        %pre $('p').addClass('myClass yourClass');
        %p
          This method is often used with
          %code .removeClass()
          to switch elements' classes from one to another, like so:
        %pre $('p').removeClass('myClass noClass').addClass('yourClass');
        %p
          Here, the
          %code myClass
          and
          %code noClass
          classes are removed from all paragraphs, while
          %code yourClass
          is added.
        %p
          As of jQuery 1.4, the
          %code .addClass()
          method allows us to set the class name by passing in a function.
        %pre
          :preserve
            $('ul li:last').addClass(function() {
              return 'item-' + $(this).index();
            });        %p
          Given an unordered list with five
          %code &lt;li&gt;
          elements, this example adds the class "item-4" to the last
          = succeed "." do
            %code &lt;li&gt;
